ANTHRAX, BOVINE - CANADA: (SASKATCHEWAN)
****************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Fri 25 Jul 2008
Source: Canadian Cattlemen -- The Beef Magazine, Farm Business
Communications [edited]
<http://www.canadiancattlemen.ca/issues/ISArticle.asp?id=87517&issue=07252008&story_id=&PC=FBC>


7 Saskatchewan bison die from anthrax
-------------------------------------
The Canadian Food Inspection Agency (CFIA) said Friday [25 Jul 2008],
7 bison on one farm in the northern Saskatchewan municipality of
Paddockwood, near Prince Albert, were confirmed Thursday [24 Jul
2008] to have died of anthrax. The dead animals make up the 2nd
separate case of anthrax poisoning [sic] in the province this week,
the CFIA said, noting one death in a cattle herd in the RM [rural
municipality] of Ponass Lake, confirmed Tuesday [22 Jul 2008]. The RM
is about 100 km (62 mi) east of Humboldt.

A farm in the RM of King George, southeast of Rosetown, was confirmed
[26 May 2008] as having the province's 1st cases of anthrax this
spring [2008] after 13 cattle died on one local farm.

Findings of anthrax in Western Canada are common, CFIA said, and the
spores that cause the disease are known to exist in soil across the
Prairies.

All suspected or confirmed cases of anthrax must be reported to the
CFIA, which recommends that as a precaution, producers should
immediately notify their veterinarians of any sudden deaths in their
herds. When anthrax is confirmed, the CFIA quarantines affected
premises during decontamination and disposal. Producers of livestock
affected by anthrax may get compensation of between CAD 100 (USD 98)
and CAD 500 (USD 490) per animal, depending on species, once CFIA
confirms disease control actions are complete.

In 2007, anthrax was reported on 23 farms in Manitoba, 6 in
Saskatchewan, and 4 in Alberta.

--
