[2]
Date: Fri 25 Jul 2008
Source: The Record, Canadian Press report [edited]
<http://news.therecord.com/article/389337>


Saskatchewan 2nd case of anthrax this week found on Prince Albert farm
----------------------------------------------------------------------
A farm north of Prince Albert is the site of Saskatchewan's 2nd case
of anthrax this week [21-27 Jul 2008]. The Canadian Food Inspection
Agency says 7 bison have tested positive for the bacteria. The food
inspection agency is at the bison ranch to implement standard disease
control measures, including quarantine.

A cow near Saskatoon tested positive earlier this week, and 13 cattle
in the Swift Current area were discovered with the disease in May
[2008].

In 2006, an anthrax outbreak in the province killed over 800 animals.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett

[Our thanks to Joe and Brent for catching these separate reports.

Considering the extensive epidemic in Saskatchewan in 2006 and
resulting soil contamination, however careful the cleanup, these 3
outbreaks are not unexpected. As you will see from their locations
below, these 3 outbreaks are well spread out in the province. Whether
we will see a rerun of 2006 depends on how carefully the ranchers
have been listening to vaccination advice.

While the Canadian policy of compensation increases reporting markedly
-- virtually nothing was reported in the decades prior to the setting
up of this Canadian scheme in the mid '60s -- latterly it has been
noted that some ranchers have only vaccinated their affected stock
after outbreaks have been occurred. There is a move to make
compensation payable _only_ when the affected rancher had vaccinated
his stock before the summer anthrax season. This makes a lot of sense.
Also it is only a matter of time until Canadian lawyers cotton on to
the fact that when diagnosis is delayed for whatever good or bad
reason, and the index ranch has some 4-6 moribund or dead cows from
anthrax, the possibility of neighbouring herds coming down with
anthrax because of foraging female mouthpart-contaminated haemophagic
flies (that is, blood-sucking horseflies) is significantly increased,
that is, as a result of a reporting failure by the index rancher. Thus
an added benefit of vaccination is as lawyer insurance ... no small
benefit in North America.

For a map of Saskatchewan go to
<http://www.fallingrain.com/world/CA/11/index.html>.
To find Paddockwood, SK, about 30 miles (48 km) NNE of Prince Albert, go to
<http://www.fallingrain.com/world/CA/11/Paddockwood.html>.
Ponass Lake is some 120 miles (193 km) due east of Saskatoon.

To find Rosetown, about 80 miles SW of Saskatoon, go to
<http://www.fallingrain.com/world/CA/11/Rosetown.html>.
King George is some 40 miles (64 km) SE of Rosetown and some 100
miles (160 km) SW of Saskatoon. - Mod.MHJ]
